kMacSystemFont, 'Inter', Roboto, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'S=
egoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol';font-size:18px;font-weight:400;line-heigh=
t:29px;text-align:left;"><p style=3D"margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0"></p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:10px 0">Hey everybody, just wanted to share why I=E2=80=99ve=
 been a little quiet the last day or so.</p><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Toda=
y I closed out the final of my multi-unit properties I=E2=80=99ve owned and=
 managed. After 30 years in the multi-unit real estate business as a side g=
ig, I=E2=80=99m now completely out of it for the first time.</p><p style=3D=
"margin:10px 0">For decades I believed in the classic three-legged stool =
=E2=80=94 and real estate was always one of the main legs. Made money in ma=
rkets, too that profit and bought multi unit apt buildings, renovated them,=
 made them cash flow and then plan was to hold forever.  So if I lost every=
thing in the markets I always had cashflow engines. That leg is gone now (a=
side from the personal real estate I keep for my own family use).</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:10px 0">The situation in San Francisco had become untenable. R=
ent control, combined with social activism, shifting legal risks, and stead=
ily rising costs, made the economics stop making sense. Not to mention the =
clear and present danger of liability. </p><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Here=
=E2=80=99s a clear example: one unit had a tenant who=E2=80=99d been there =
42 years. We were collecting $900 a month while the unit=E2=80=99s market r=
eality was closer to $5,000+. Every month it was costing me roughly $4,100 =
net a month for decades =E2=80=94 pure dead money. </p><p style=3D"margin:1=
0px 0">In addition, imagine a property I bought for say $1M over 25 years a=
go, the value has only doubled at best because rent control choked apprecia=
tion. CAGR =3D 2.8114% which is 12% under what I need to tread water. Rem i=
n SF If those had been single-family homes instead, they likely would have =
sold for 3=E2=80=934 times as much, even with no rental income.</p><p style=
=3D"margin:10px 0">Final note, SF is red hot due to the AI Boom... so I con=
sider it a top of the market and next year RE could probably tank so I was =
happy to exit before the summer ended. </p><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Betwe=
en that math, higher property taxes and utilities, outrageous insurance for=
 $10K to $20K per building, and increasing liability, it just didn=E2=80=99=
t make sense to keep holding. Better to sell, take the capital, and put it =
somewhere with real upside.</p><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">If this were almo=
st anywhere else in the U.S., the decision might have been different. But r=
ent control in San Francisco proved to be the kiss of death for landlords t=
rying to run viable real estate business.  Same thing in NYC, my friends wh=
o had multi properties there they are selling them for a fraction of what t=
hey were worth a few years ago just to escape New York. </p><p style=3D"mar=
gin:10px 0">I don=E2=80=99t want to sound like some ruthless capitalist her=
e =E2=80=94 I genuinely like helping people and I took care of that lady fo=
r decades. But right as I was trying to sell the property she was in, she s=
tepped in and stabbed me in the back by lying to a property inspector and d=
erailed one of the sales. It=E2=80=99s a weird world. That changed me... an=
d rem what really put me off in the end was the liability - they are too us=
ed to hand outs and will bite the hand that feeds.  </p><p style=3D"margin:=
10px 0">Just wanted to share the portfolio shift. Excited to move forward w=
ith far cleaner far higher ROI capital allocation.</p><p style=3D"margin:10=
px 0"></p><p></p></div></td></tr>
